{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014ThWkF4huhyYkoqVTe4qra","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Graph boost is in `RecallOrchestrator` (auto-recall path), not in `MemoryRetriever` (search path). The task says to enable graph-boosted recall — the natural integration point is the `_ranked_search` in TappsMCP where we can pass through the `RecallOrchestrator` for search, or more practically, add graph boost logic to the ranked search path.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the architecture: `RecallOrchestrator.recall()` is the auto-recall path (pre-prompt injection). The `_ranked_search` uses `MemoryRetriever` directly. The graph boost is in `RecallOrchestrator._apply_graph_boost()` which works on the memories returned from injection.\n\nThe simplest approach is:\n1. Add `relation_count` to `StoreHealthReport` in tapps-brain and populate in `health()`\n2. In TappsMCP's `_ranked_search`, after getting results from `MemoryRetriever`, check relation count and apply graph boost if >= 10 relations\n3. Surface `relation_count` in `_handle_health()` response\n\nLet me check if `MemoryStore` exposes `count_relations` or if we need to call through `_persistence`."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1048,"cache_read_input_tokens":52628,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1048},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"327621aa-924c-4bfb-b348-3a4acf890b54","uuid":"cdcc4d68-97b5-407c-a373-4cb538a4f626"}
